---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import Terminal from '../../components/Terminal.astro';
---

<DocsLayout
  title="CLI Surface"
  description="ostk's CLI is two surfaces composed — a stable agent-callable System ABI and a free-evolving operator overlay. Below: five workflows showing how verbs from each compose into the things you actually do."
  sectionLabel="REFERENCE // CLI"
  activeTab="commands"
>
  <p class="font-headline text-lg text-on-surface-variant italic leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-8">
    The CLI is two surfaces composed. Five workflows show how their verbs chain into what you actually do.
  </p>

  <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-12">
    For verb-by-verb help, run <code class="text-primary">ostk help &lt;verb&gt;</code> (System ABI; man pages) or <code class="text-primary">ostk &lt;verb&gt; --help</code> (operator overlay; clap-style). For the full agent-callable schema, <code class="text-primary">ostk abi list</code>. This page is about how the verbs compose.
  </p>

  <!-- Workflow 01 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">WORKFLOW_01 // BOOT_A_PROJECT</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">First time on a repo. Get a working setup.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Three commands. <code class="text-primary">ostk init</code> creates <code class="text-primary">.ostk/</code> with a humanfile, an Agentfile, and pin caps. <code class="text-primary">ostk daemon</code> starts the kernel; if it's already running, the next ostk RPC will reuse it. <code class="text-primary">ostk tui</code> attaches and gives you the live window — fleet, work queue, tack input.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline">$ </span>cd ~/projects/your-repo
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk init                <span class="text-outline"># creates .ostk/ — humanfile, agentfile, pin caps</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk daemon &amp;            <span class="text-outline"># anchor process, holds socket + scheduler + registries</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk tui                 <span class="text-outline"># attach the terminal UI</span></pre>
    </Terminal>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        <code class="text-primary">init</code> (creates <code class="text-primary">.ostk/</code> substrate) · <code class="text-primary">daemon</code> (formerly <code class="text-primary">listen</code>; the anchor process) · <code class="text-primary">tui</code> (transient client; attach/detach freely).
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/commands/init.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/commands_use/listen.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/commands/tui.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Workflow 02 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">WORKFLOW_02 // DRIVE_AN_AGENT_OVER_MCP</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">You already use Claude Code, Cursor, or another MCP client. Wire ostk in once.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      The kernel exposes itself as an MCP server over stdio. Your agent tool launches <code class="text-primary">ostk mcp</code> as a subprocess and the bridge forwards to the running daemon (or serves in-process if no daemon is up). After restart, the agent's tool surface gains <code class="text-primary">mcp__ostk__bash</code>, <code class="text-primary">fs_ops</code>, <code class="text-primary">read</code>, <code class="text-primary">search</code> and the rest of the kernel verbs — every call audited, every write gen-tracked, every escape pin-checked.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline"># in your client's MCP config (e.g. .mcp.json)</span>
{`{ "mcpServers": { "ostk": { "command": "ostk", "args": ["mcp"] } } }`}

<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk mcp diag            <span class="text-outline"># reconcile the kernel's tool surface with CORE_SEED_LANGUAGE</span></pre>
    </Terminal>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        <code class="text-primary">mcp</code> (stdio bridge to the daemon) · the System ABI (the verbs your client sees) · pin caps + gen_table layered transparently. Full wiring guide at <a href="/docs/mcp" class="text-primary hover:underline">/docs/mcp</a>.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/main.rs</code> (<code>Commands::Mcp</code>), <code class="text-primary">src/serve/server.rs</code> (<code>run_mcp_bridge</code>), <code class="text-primary">src/commands_use/mcp_diag.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Workflow 03 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">WORKFLOW_03 // RUN_A_ONE_SHOT</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">You have an Agentfile that describes a worker. Run it.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      An Agentfile is a declarative spec: identity, capabilities, model, budget, task. <code class="text-primary">ostk run</code> spawns the worker, applies pin caps from the file, and runs the agent loop until completion or budget cap. Every action lands in <code class="text-primary">.ostk/journal.jsonl</code> attributed to the worker. <code class="text-primary">ostk learn</code> can discover sandbox restrictions by observing the worker's filesystem access — useful when you don't know yet which paths the worker actually needs.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk agentfile new fix-bug-27 &gt; .ostk/agents/fix-bug-27.toml
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>$EDITOR .ostk/agents/fix-bug-27.toml   <span class="text-outline"># declare task, model, budget, pins</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk run .ostk/agents/fix-bug-27.toml</pre>
    </Terminal>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        <code class="text-primary">agentfile new / lint / show / validate</code> (lifecycle) · <code class="text-primary">run</code> (spawns the agent loop) · pin caps · the agent's drain snapshot at every turn boundary so the worker can be revived if the daemon restarts.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/commands/run.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/commands/agentfile_cmd.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/commands/learn.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Workflow 04 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">WORKFLOW_04 // OBSERVE_THE_FLEET</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">Fleet's running. What's it doing right now?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      <code class="text-primary">ostk ps</code> gives you the live process table with the Process Identity Quad — pid, ppid, pgid, sid — the same shape POSIX gave you for shell processes. <code class="text-primary">ostk pstree</code> renders the fleet as a tree rooted at live ppid edges. <code class="text-primary">ostk show &lt;keyword&gt;</code> is the universal query — find an agent, a needle, a decision, a commit by name. The audit chain itself is just <code class="text-primary">tail -f .ostk/journal.jsonl</code>.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk ps                  <span class="text-outline"># pid ppid pgid sid alias status</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk pstree              <span class="text-outline"># fleet as a tree</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk show fix-bug-27     <span class="text-outline"># find anything by name/keyword</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>tail -f .ostk/journal.jsonl   <span class="text-outline"># the audit chain</span></pre>
    </Terminal>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Process Identity Quad (invariant VI) makes <code class="text-primary">ps</code>/<code class="text-primary">pstree</code>/<code class="text-primary">pkill</code> mean what they mean in POSIX · the observation substrate projects journal rows onto a VFS namespace · <code class="text-primary">show</code> queries the projection. No polling, no replication.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/commands/ps.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/commands/pstree.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/commands/show.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Workflow 05 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">WORKFLOW_05 // SIGN_AND_SHIP</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">You want to hand a snapshot to someone else and have them verify it.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      <code class="text-primary">ostk bail pack</code> bundles a signed, portable OS package — Agentfiles, pin caps, the audit chain slice that produced them, your operator signature. Send the bail file. Recipient runs <code class="text-primary">ostk bail verify</code>; the chain replays, the signature checks, and they get a yes/no on whether what's inside matches what you sent. <code class="text-primary">ostk os audit</code> verifies your local journal end-to-end — every prev_hash, every Ed25519 signature.
    </p>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-outline italic max-w-xl mb-4">
      <code class="text-primary">application/v1</code> generalizes this — a content-addressed signed application directory with declared capabilities and supervisor trees, installed via <code class="text-primary">ostk app *</code> verbs. Spec is <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/blob/main/docs/spec/llmos-application.md" class="text-primary hover:underline">ratified</a>; CLI verbs land in a future release.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk bail pack --out fix-bug-27.bail
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>scp fix-bug-27.bail other-machine:
<span class="text-outline">other-machine $ </span>ostk bail verify fix-bug-27.bail
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk os audit            <span class="text-outline"># local: end-to-end journal integrity check</span></pre>
    </Terminal>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        <code class="text-primary">bail pack/verify</code> (signed package) · journal hash chain (audit-trail integrity) · Ed25519 in-process signing · <code class="text-primary">os audit</code> (replay verification) · <code class="text-primary">trust</code> namespace for key rotation and revocation.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/commands/bail.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/commands/os.rs</code> (<code>audit</code> subcommand), <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/signing.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/util/audit.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The two surfaces -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">THE_TWO_SURFACES</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">System ABI + operator overlay.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-6">
      Every verb above belongs to one of two surfaces. The <strong class="text-on-surface">System ABI</strong> is the agent-callable layer — 27 verbs at v1.0.0, schema'd, hash-stamped, frozen between major releases. Agents reach it through the MCP bridge. The <strong class="text-on-surface">operator overlay</strong> is the human-driver — clap-style commands free to evolve, frequently aliased and renamed (<code class="text-primary">ostk listen</code> → <code class="text-primary">daemon</code>, <code class="text-primary">ostk mcp call</code> → <code class="text-primary">driver call</code>, etc.). Verbs that begin with <code class="text-primary">_</code> (e.g. <code class="text-primary">_agent</code>) are kernel-internal primitives, hidden from <code class="text-primary">--help</code>.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-px bg-surface-variant max-w-2xl">
      <div class="bg-surface-container p-5">
        <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">SYSTEM_ABI</div>
        <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-3 leading-relaxed">
          27 verbs. Agent-callable through MCP. Stable schema between majors.
        </p>
        <div class="font-body text-[11px] text-secondary space-y-1">
          <div><code class="text-primary">ostk abi list</code> — all 27 with signatures</div>
          <div><code class="text-primary">ostk abi show &lt;verb&gt;</code> — full schema</div>
          <div><code class="text-primary">ostk abi version</code> — current ABI hash</div>
          <div><code class="text-primary">ostk abi diff &lt;ref&gt;</code> — vs git ref</div>
          <div><code class="text-primary">ostk help &lt;verb&gt;</code> — man page</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-surface-container p-5">
        <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">OPERATOR_OVERLAY</div>
        <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-3 leading-relaxed">
          Clap-style operator commands. Evolves freely. Free to alias, rename, deprecate.
        </p>
        <div class="font-body text-[11px] text-secondary space-y-1">
          <div><code class="text-primary">ostk --help</code> — full surface</div>
          <div><code class="text-primary">ostk &lt;verb&gt; --help</code> — per-verb</div>
          <div><code class="text-primary">ostk hs &lt;cmd&gt;</code> — short alias</div>
          <div><code class="text-primary">ostk show &lt;keyword&gt;</code> — universal query</div>
          <div><code class="text-primary">ostk inspect</code> — runtime introspection</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="font-body text-xs text-outline mt-6 max-w-xl">
      The split is what lets the operator surface ship daily improvements while the agent-callable surface stays stable. Agents see ABI, not CLI. Verbs change names; ABI hashes change versions.
    </p>
  </section>

